---
name: planner schema validation demo
description: Exercises planner argument-schema validation by attaching `recover` blocks for every PlanningFailureCode the planner is allowed to raise.
goal: Prove the planner never executes ill-formed proposals and that each rejection lands in a typed audit note.
parameters: pull request
vocabulary: comprehensive_workflows.merconfig
---
## Snapshot

- open the audit log for the pull request.
- inspect the ci status of the pull request.

## Plan with strict argument validation

- plan careful repair for the pull request.

  recover from "planning.missing_tool_argument":
    record an audit note about the pull request because of "planner forgot a required argument".
  recover from "planning.unexpected_tool_argument":
    record an audit note about the pull request because of "planner sent an unexpected argument".
  recover from "planning.invalid_tool_argument_type":
    record an audit note about the pull request because of "planner sent the wrong type for an argument".
  recover from "planning.tool_not_registered":
    record an audit note about the pull request because of "planner asked for an unknown tool".
  recover from "planning.too_many_actions":
    record an audit note about the pull request because of "planner proposed too many actions in one step".

## Run the bounded autonomy loop with the same scoped toolset

- autonomously execute careful repair for the pull request.

  recover from "planning.max_steps_exceeded":
    record an audit note about the pull request because of "autonomy loop exhausted the step budget".

## Audit close

- close the audit log for the pull request.

## Sub-workflows

To plan careful repair for a pull request, with discretion:
  Inspect the ci status and failing jobs. Propose only apply smallest repair and notify channel actions, with all required arguments and the correct types. Never propose unrelated tools.

To autonomously execute careful repair for a pull request, with autonomy until the ci status is passed re-plan after 2 failures max 5:
  Apply at most one bounded repair per step. Pass exactly the arguments declared by the tool's signature.
